summary:
The Security Council:
Recalling previous resolutions and statements on Burundi, reaffirms the Arusha Peace and Reconciliation Agreement of August 2000 as the basis for conflict resolution. 
Expressing deep concern at ongoing violence and insecurity, and noting regional implications, it reiterates support for former President Nelson Mandela's facilitation efforts and the Secretary-General's enhanced role in Burundi. 
Commending the Organization of African Unity/African Union's efforts, it welcomes the 11 October 2001 Pretoria Summit's agreement on the transitional government's framework and structure. 
The Council: 
1. Reaffirms strong support for the 1 November 2001 transitional government installation; 
2. Calls on parties to end violence against civilians; 
3. Calls on FDD and FNL to cease hostilities, enter negotiations, and join the peace process; 
4. Endorses South Africa's efforts and supports an interim multinational security presence; 
5. Requests Burundi's government to inform on progress establishing an all-Burundian protection force; 
6. Reiterates willingness to consider further contributions to the peace process; 
7. Urges the international community to provide additional assistance; 
8. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
